'''Shane Michael Gillis''' (born December 11, 1987) is an American stand-up comedian, actor, and podcaster known for his [[Netflix]] comedy specials and series ''[[Tires (TV series)|Tires]]''.

Gillis started performing comedy in 2012, and in 2016, along with fellow stand-up comedian Matt McCusker, began co-hosting ''Matt and Shane's Secret Podcast'', the most subscribed-to podcast on [[Patreon]] as of 2024.<ref name=kelefa>[[Kelefa Sanneh|Sanneh, Kelefa]] (September 26, 2022). [[iarchive:sanneh-kelefa-the-joker-the-rise-and-fall-of-shane-gillis-the-new-yorker-sep.-26-2022-pp.-30-36|"The Joker: The Fall and Rise of Shane Gillis."]] Annals of Comedy. ''[[The New Yorker]]'', vol. 98, no. 30, pp. 30–36. [https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2022/09/26/shane-gillis-fall-and-rise/amp Audio online.]</ref><ref name="NYT - How Shane Gillis Both Plays to and Mocks Red Staters">{{Cite Q|Q122656232|access-date=2023-09-18}}</ref> 
Gillis had a breakout year in 2019; the [[Just for Laughs]] festival in [[Montreal]] named him one of its "New Faces" in July, and in September he was announced as a newly-hired cast member on [[NBC]]'s sketch comedy series ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (SNL). He subsequently became the subject of a controversy and was fired after five days at SNL due to backlash over a 2018 clip from his podcast in which derogatory language, such as Asian [[List of ethnic slurs|ethnic slurs]], were used, sparking a discussion on context and intent when certain topics are used for comedic purposes.<ref>{{cite web|first=Vanessa|last=Romo|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/16/761367838/comedian-shane-gillis-fired-from-saturday-night-live-for-racist-remarks|title=Comedian Shane Gillis Fired From 'Saturday Night Live' For Racist Remarks|website=[[NPR]]|date=September 16, 2019|access-date=September 17, 2019| quote = {{'}}After talking with Shane Gillis, we have decided that he will not be joining SNL,{{'}} a spokesperson said in a statement on behalf of producer Lorne Michaels.}}</ref><ref name="HollywoodReporter">{{Cite web|first1=Shrahreh|last1=Drury|first2=Rick|last2=Porter|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/shane-gillis-at-saturday-night-live-racial-homophobic-slurs-podcast-1239506/|title=Shane Gillis Out at 'Saturday Night Live' Following Racial, Homophobic Slurs in Podcast|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 16, 2019|access-date=July 7, 2022}}</ref>

In 2020, Gillis launched the online sketch series ''Gilly & Keeves'' in collaboration with filmmaker John McKeever, and he released his first comedy special, ''Shane Gillis: Live in Austin'', on [[YouTube]] in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/shane-gillis-live-in-austin-review/|title=Shane Gillis Live in Austin Review: New Standup Special Is Dark, Funny and Free on YouTube|date=September 5, 2021|website=MovieWeb}}</ref> In 2023, his second comedy special, ''Shane Gillis: Beautiful Dogs'', was released on [[Netflix]]. As of 2024, Gillis has starred in the Netflix comedy series ''[[Tires (TV series)|Tires]]'', which he co-created with McKeever. The first season premiered in

